s produced by Trackmasters]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Rashad Smith]]\n[[Category:East Coast hip hop albums]]\n[[Category:Hardcore hip hop albums]]\n[[Category:Concept albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2017}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Ready to Die\n| type       = Studio\n| artist     = [[The Notorious B.I.G.]]\n| cover      = Ready To Die.jpg\n| border     = yes\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|1994|09|13}}\n| recorded   = 1993\u20131994\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[The Hit Factory]] and [[D&D Studios]], New York City\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[East Coast hip hop]]\n*[[gangsta rap]]\n*[[hardcore hip hop]]\n}}\n| length     = 69:05\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Bad Boy Records|Bad Boy]]|[[Arista Records|Arista]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[Mister Cee|Mr. Cee]] <small>(associate [[Executive producer|exec.]])</small>  |[[Masta Ace Incorporated|Bluez Brothers]]|[[Sean \"Puffy\" Combs]] <small>(also [[Executive producer|exec.]])</small>|[[DJ Premier]]|[[Easy Mo Bee]]|[[Rashad Smith]]|[[Lord Finesse]]|[[Trackmasters|Poke]]|Darnell Scott|[[Chucky Thompson]]}}\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Life After Death]]\n| next_year  = 1997\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Ready to Die\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Juicy (The Notorious B.I.G. song)|Juicy]]\n | single1date = August 9, 1994\n | single2     = [[Big Poppa]] / Warning \n | single2date = February 20, 1995\n | single3     = [[One More Chance (The Notorious B.I.G. song)|One More Chance]]\n | single3date = June 6, 1995\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Ready to Die''''' is the debut studio album by American rapper [[The Notorious B.I.G.]], released on September 13, 1994, by [[Bad Boy Records|Bad Boy]] and [[Arista Records]]. The album features production by Bad Boy founder [[Sean Combs|Sean \"Puffy\" Combs]], [[Easy Mo Bee]], [[Chucky Thompson]], [[DJ Premier]], and [[Lord Finesse]], among others. It was recorded from 1993 to 1994 at [[The Hit Factory]] and [[D&D Studios]] in [[New York City]]. The partly autobiographical album tells the story of the rapper's experiences as a young criminal, and was the only studio album released during his lifetime, as he was murdered sixteen days before the release of his second album ''[[Life After Death]]'' in 1997.\n\n''Ready to Die'' peaked at number 15 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] and was subject to critical acclaim and soon a commercial success. Three singles were released from the album: \"[[Juicy (The Notorious B.I.G. song)|Juicy]]\", \"[[Big Poppa]]\", \"[[One More Chance (The Notorious B.I.G. song)|One More Chance]]\" and a promotional track of Biggie: \"[[Warning (The Notorious B.I.G. song)|Warning]]\". \"Juicy\", the lead single, peaked at number 27 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], number 14 on [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Singles & Tracks]] and reached number 3 on the [[Hot Rap Singles]].<ref name=\"AMG-Singles\" /> \"Big Poppa\" was a hit on multiple charts, peaking at number six on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and also being nominated for a [[Grammy Award for Best Rap Solo Performance]] at the [[1996 Grammy Awards]]. The Notorious B.I.G.'s lyrics on the album were generally praised by critics, with many praising his story-telling ability.\n\nIn April 2018, ''Ready to Die'' was certified [[RIAA certification|6x Platinum]] by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA). The album was significant for revitalizing the [[East Coast hip hop]] scene, amid [[West Coast hip hop]]'s commercial dominance,<ref name=\"AMG-Bio\">Steve Huey. [{{AllMusic|class=artist|id=p44889|pure_url=yes}} The Notorious B.I.G. > Biography]. AllMusic. Retrieved March 17, 2007</ref> and has been ranked by many critics as one of the greatest hip hop albums, as well as one of the greatest albums of all time. ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' ranked it number 134 on its list of the [[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|500 Greatest Albums of All Time]].<ref name=\":0\" /> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' included it on its list of the All-TIME 100 Albums.\n\n==Background and recording==\nThe album was recorded in [[New York City]] (mainly at [[The Hit Factory]]) in two stages between 1993 and 1994. In 1994, Biggie was 21 years old when he recorded the album. In 1992, Biggie was signed to the [[Uptown Records]] label by [[A&R]] [[Sean \"Puffy\" Combs]]. Biggie started recording his debut album in 1993 in New York, after making numerous guest appearances among his label-mates' singles around that time. The first tracks recorded include the album's darker, less radio-friendly content (including \"Ready to Die,\" \"Gimme the Loot\" and \"Things Done Changed\"). In these sessions, ''[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]'' magazine describe an \"inexperienced, higher-pitched\" Biggie sounding \"hungry and paranoid\".<ref name=xxl />\n\nWhen executive producer [[Sean \"Puffy\" Combs]] was fired from Uptown, Biggie's career hung in limbo, as the album was only partially completed. After a brief period [[Illicit drug trade|dealing drugs]] in [[North Carolina]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Menconi |first1=David |title=Notorious B.I.G.'s Raleigh days, revisited |url=http://www.newsobserver.com/entertainment/music-news-reviews/on-the-beat-blog/article137454708.html |website=newsobserver |language=en |date=January 25, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170423173943/http://www.newsobserver.com/entertainment/music-news-reviews/on-the-beat-blog/article137454708.html |archivedate=April 23, 2017 }}</ref> Biggie returned to the studio the following year on Combs' new [[Bad Boy Records]] label possessing \"a smoother, more confident vocal tone\" and completed the album. In this stage, the more commercial-sounding tracks of the album were recorded, including the album's singles. Between the two stages, ''XXL'' writes that Biggie moved from writing his lyrics in notebooks to [[freestyling]] them from memory.<ref name=\"xxl\">{{cite web|last1=Duncan |first1=Andrea |title=The Making of 'Ready To Die': Family Business |url=http://xxlmag.com/online/?p=408 |website=XXL Mag |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061110093816/http://xxlmag.com/online/?p=408 |archivedate=November 10, 2006 }}</ref>\n\nThe album was released with a cover depicting an infant resembling the artist, though sporting an [[afro]], which pertains to the album's concept of the artist's life from birth to his death. It has been listed as among the best album covers in hip hop.<ref>{{cite book|first1=Sacha |last=Jenkins|title=Ego trip's book of rap lists|date=1999|publisher=St. Martin's Griffin|location=New York|isbn=978-0-312-24298-5|page=[https://archive.org/details/egotripsbookofra00jenk/page/167 167]|edition=1st|url=https://archive.org/details/egotripsbookofra00jenk/page/167}}</ref>\n\n===Lawsuits and sample removal===\nOn March 24, 2006, [[Bridgeport Music]] and [[Westbound Records]] won a federal lawsuit against [[Bad Boy Records]] for copyright infringement, with a jury deciding that Combs and Bad Boy had illegally used samples for the production of the songs \"Ready to Die\", \"Machine Gun Funk\", and \"Gimme the Loot\".<ref name=HipHopDX1>{{cite web|last=J-23 |title=Court After Death: Biggie Being Sued |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.3780/title.court-after-death-biggie-being-sued |work=HipHopDX |accessdate=October 5, 2013 |date=December 30, 2005 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131007005023/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.3780/title.court-after-death-biggie-being-sued |archivedate=October 7, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=bryantimes>{{cite news|last=AP|title=Judge halts sales of Notorious B.I.G. album after jury finds song snippet used without permission|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=VvkvAAAAIBAJ&sjid=iUkDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5587%2C2536180|accessdate=October 5, 2013|newspaper=The Bryan Times|date=March 24, 2006}}</ref> The jury awarded $4.2&nbsp;million in punitive and direct damages to the two plaintiffs, and federal judge [[Todd J. Campbell|Todd Campbell]] enacted an immediate sales ban on the album and tracks in question.<ref name=bryantimes /> On appeal, the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit|Sixth Circuit]] found the damages unconstitutionally high and in violation of [[due process]] and remanded the case, at which point Campbell reduced them by $2.8&nbsp;million; however, the verdict was upheld.<ref name=exclusiverights>{{cite web|title=Westbound Records awarded 688k in punitive damages for Notorious B.I.G. sample |url=http://www.exclusiverights.net/2009/04/westbound-records-awarded-688k-in-punitive-damages-for-notorious-big-sample/ |publisher=Exclusive Rights |accessdate=October 5, 2013 |date=April 13, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091125140936/http://www.exclusiverights.net/2009/04/westbound-records-awarded-688k-in-punitive-damages-for-notorious-big-sample/ |archivedate=November 25, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Bailey |first=Jonathan |title=04/18: On Appeal, Damages for Unauthorized \"Ready to Die\" Sample Reduced by $2,811,477 |url=http://www.badboyblog.com/item/2009/4/18/on-appeal-damages-for-unauthorized-ready-to-die-sample-reduced-by-2-811-477 |publisher=Bad Boy Blog |accessdate=October 5, 2013 |date=April 18, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131007012230/http://www.badboyblog.com/item/2009/4/18/on-appeal-damages-for-unauthorized-ready-to-die-sample-reduced-by-2-811-477 |archivedate=October 7, 2013 }}</ref> All versions of the album released since the lawsuit are without the disputed samples.<ref name=iTunes>{{cite web|title=iTunes \u2013 Music \u2013 Ready to Die \u2013 The Remaster by The Notorious B.I.G. |url=https://itunes.apple.com/en/album/ready-to-die-the-remaster/id204669326 |publisher=Apple Inc. |accessdate=October 5, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023111921/https://itunes.apple.com/en/album/ready-to-die-the-remaster/id204669326 |archivedate=October 23, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nAlthough a [[fair use]] issue, Combs and Bad Boy never raised the legal concept of the fair use doctrine in their defense.<ref name=exclusiverights /> This decision was questioned by some legal experts: Anthony Falzone of the [[Fair Use Project]] at [[Stanford Law School]] criticized Combs and Bad Boy for not defending the legality of sampling and suggested that they might have refused to raise such a defense because they feared it could later imperil their control over their own music.<ref name=Falzone>{{cite web|last=Falzone |first=Anthony |title=Why, Diddy? Why? |url=http://cyberlaw.stanford.edu/node/5581 |publisher=The Center for Internet and Society |accessdate=October 5, 2013 |date=October 18, 2007 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131007051128/http://cyberlaw.stanford.edu/node/5581 |archivedate=October 7, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nOn April 2, 2014, [[Leroy Hutson|Lee Hutson]] of [[The Impressions]] filed a multimillion-dollar copyright infringement suit against Combs, Bad Boy Records, and the estate of the late [[The Notorious B.I.G.|Notorious B.I.G.]] for copyright infringement, alleging that his song \"[[The Man!|Can't Say Enough About Mom]]\" was illegally sampled in the production of the song \"The What\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Beekman |first=Daniel |title=Former Impressions singer Lee Hutson slaps hip-hop mogul Diddy, Bad Boy Entertainment and estate of Notorious B.I.G. with copyright infringement lawsuit |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/music-arts/b-g-bucks-ripoff-lawsuit-article-1.1743783 |accessdate=April 8, 2014 |newspaper=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]] |date=April 2, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408212629/http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/music-arts/b-g-bucks-ripoff-lawsuit-article-1.1743783 |archivedate=April 8, 2014 }}</ref> The estate countersued in turn, claiming the sample as used was short, adapted, and supplemented, and thus subject to fair use,<ref>{{cite news|last=Gardner |first=Eriq |title=Notorious B.I.G. Estate Files Pre-emptive Lawsuit Over Song Sample (Exclusive) |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/notorious-big-estate-files-pre-692525 |accessdate=April 8, 2014 |newspaper=The Hollywood Reporter |date=April 1, 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140403203054/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/notorious-big-estate-files-pre-692525 |archivedate=April 3, 2014 }}</ref> a legal tactic not pursued previously.<ref name=Falzone />\n\n==Composition==\n\n===Production===\nThe production on the album was mainly handled by [[Easy Mo Bee]] and The Hitmen. Cheo H. Coker of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' depicted the beats as \"heavy bottomed and slick, but B.I.G.'s rhymes are the showstoppers. The tracks only enhance them, whether it's the live bass driving a menacing undercurrent or [the] use of bluesy guitar and wah-wah feedback\" and that the production is used to \"push the rapper to new heights.\"<ref name=RollingStone94>{{cite journal|last=Coker |first=Cheo H. |authorlink=Cheo Hodari Coker |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/notoriousbig/albums/album/192664/review/5946007/ready_to_die |title=Notorious B.I.G.: Ready To Die |journal=[[Rolling Stone]] |location=New York |date=November 3, 1994 |accessdate=December 30, 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090114112549/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/notoriousbig/albums/album/192664/review/5946007/ready_to_die |archivedate=January 14, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The production is mainly [[sampling (music)|sample]]-based with the samples varying from the [[percussion]] of [[funk music|funk]] tracks to the vocals of hip hop songs. Steve Huey presented some criticism over the beats, stating that the \"deliberate beats do get a little samey, but it hardly matters: this is Biggie's show\".<ref name=AMG />\n\n===Lyrical themes===\nThe Notorious B.I.G.'s lyrics on the album were generally praised by critics. Many critics applauded his story-telling ability such as AllMusic writer Steve Huey, who stated \"His raps are easy to understand, but his skills are hardly lacking\u2014he has a loose, easy flow and a talent for piling multiple rhymes on top of one another in quick succession\". He also went on to mention that his lyrics are \"firmly rooted in reality, but play like [a] scene from a movie\".<ref name=AMG /> [[Tour\u00e9]], writing for ''The New York Times'', referred to The Notorious B.I.G., proclaiming that he stood out from other rappers because \"his lyrics mix autobiographical details about crime and violence with emotional honesty, telling how he felt while making a living as a drug dealer\".<ref name=NYTimes /> The album is also noted for its dark tone and sinister sense of depression.<ref name=AMG /> In the original ''Rolling Stone'' review, Cheo H Coker declared that he \"maintains a consistent level of tension by juxtaposing emotional highs and lows\".<ref name=RollingStone94 /> \"Things Done Changed\" was also one of the few hip hop songs in The Norton Anthology of African American Literature.<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Gates Jr.|editor1-first=Henry Louis|title=The Norton Anthology of African American literature|date=2004|publisher=Norton|location=New York, NY [u.a.]|isbn=978-0-393-97778-3|edition=2.}}</ref>\n\nThe lyrics on ''Ready to Die'' tend to deal with violence, drug dealing, women, alcohol and [[cannabis (drug)|marijuana]] use, and other elements of Notorious B.I.G.'s environment. He rapped about these topics in \"clear, sparse terms, allowing the lyrics to hit the first time you hear them\".<ref name=\"RollingStone94\" /> The album contains a loose concept starting out with an intro that details his birth, his early childhood, his adolescence and his life at the point of the album's release.<ref name=NYTimes>{{cite web|last1=TOURE |title=Biggie Smalls, Rap's Man of the Moment |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/12/18/arts/pop-music-biggie-smalls-rap-s-man-of-the-moment.html |work=The New York Times |accessdate=July 11, 2017 |date=December 18, 1994 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170701024448/http://www.nytimes.com/1994/12/18/arts/pop-music-biggie-smalls-rap-s-man-of-the-moment.html |archivedate=July 1, 2017 }}</ref> Songs on the album range from homicide narratives (\"Warning\") to braggadocios [[battle rap]]s (\"The What,\" \"Unbelievable\"). The final song was \"Suicidal Thoughts\", a song where The Notorious B.I.G. contemplates and finally commits [[suicide]].\n\n==Commercial performance==\n''Ready to Die'' shipped 57,000 units in its first week of release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stopthebreaks.com/hip-hop-features/ranking-notorious-big-first-week-album-sales/|title=Sky\u2019s the Limit: Ranking The Notorious B.I.G. First Week Album Sales|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140716033444/http://www.stopthebreaks.com/hip-hop-features/ranking-notorious-big-first-week-album-sales/|archivedate=July 16, 2014|accessdate=2014-06-21}}</ref> However, it was then certified Gold by the [[RIAA]] only two months after its release on November 16, 1994, and was certified double Platinum on October 16, 1995, only a year and one month after its release.<ref name=\"RIAA-Singles\" /> ''Ready to Die'' was then certified triple Platinum on August 26, 1998 and was later certified 4\u00d7 Platinum by the [[RIAA]] on October 19, 1999.<ref name=\"RIAA-Singles\" />\n\n==Singles==\n{{Listen|filename=Notorious B.I.G. - Juicy.ogg|description=The album's [[lead single]] is a [[rags to riches]] narrative, with music that [[sampling (music)|samples]] [[Mtume]]'s 1983 song \"[[Juicy Fruit (song)|Juicy Fruit]]\".<ref name=\"Huey\" />|title=\"Juicy\"}}\n\nThree singles were released from the album: \"[[Juicy (The Notorious B.I.G. song)|Juicy]]\", \"[[Big Poppa]]\", \"[[One More Chance (The Notorious B.I.G. song)|One More Chance]]\" and a promotional track of Biggie: \"[[Warning (The Notorious B.I.G. song)|Warning]]\". According to ''[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]'' the more commercial sound of the singles compared to the rest of the album was a result of encouragement by Combs during the later recording sessions in which they were recorded.<ref name=xxl />\n\n\"Juicy\" was released as the lead single on August 8, 1994. It peaked at number 27 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], number 14 on [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Singles & Tracks]] and reached number 3 on the [[Hot Rap Singles]].<ref name=AMG-Singles>[{{AllMusic|class=album|id=r203800|pure_url=yes}} Ready to Die \u2013 Billboard Singles]. AllMusic. Retrieved May 15, 2008.</ref> It shipped 500,000 copies in the United States and the RIAA certified it [[RIAA certification|Gold]] on November 16, 1994.<ref name=RIAA-Singles>{{cite web|title=Gold & Platinum \u2013 RIAA|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&ar=NOTORIOUS+B.I.G.&ti=READY+TO+DIE|website=RIAA|accessdate=July 11, 2017}}</ref> Produced by Combs, it features a prominent sample of \"[[Juicy Fruit (song)|Juicy Fruit]]\" as performed by [[James Mtume]]. AllMusic's Steve Huey stated that, along with the other singles, it was an \"upbeat, commercial moment\", calling it a \"rags-to-riches chronicle\".<ref name=AMG>[{{AllMusic|class=album|id=r203800|last=Huey|first=Steve|label=Ready to Die > Overview| accessdate=May 15, 2008|pure_url=yes}}</ref> Andrew Kameka, of HipHopDX.com, stated that the song was one of his \"greatest and most-revealing songs\" and went on to say it was a \"Part-autobiography, part-declaration-of-success. It document[s] the star's transition from Brooklyn knucklehead to magazine cover story.\"<ref name=HipHopDX>{{cite web|last1=Kameka |first1=Andrew |title=The Notorious B.I.G. \u2013 Ready To Die |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/reviews/id.761/title.the-notorious-b-i-g-ready-to-die |website=HipHopDX |accessdate=July 11, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100116125345/http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/reviews/id.761/title.the-notorious-b-i-g-ready-to-die |archivedate=January 16, 2010 }}</ref> Producer [[Pete Rock]], who was commissioned to remix the track, alleged that Puffy stole the idea for the original song's beat after hearing it from him during a visit. Rock explained this in an interview with ''[[Wax Poetics]]'':<ref>[http://peterock.tribe.net/thread/032f66d2-a223-400c-a902-fe166be14676 Wax Poetic interview \u2013 Pete Rock \u2013 tribe.net] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120220125121/http://peterock.tribe.net/thread/032f66d2-a223-400c-a902-fe166be14676 |date=February 20, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n{{quote|I did the original version, didn't get credit for it. They came to my house, heard the beat going on the drum machine, it's the same story. You come downstairs at my crib, you hear music. He heard that shit and the next thing you know it comes out. They had me do a remix, but I tell people, and I will fight it to the end, that I did the original version of that. I'm not mad at anybody, I just want the correct credit.|}}\n\n\"Big Poppa\" was released as the second single on December 24, 1994 and like the previous single, it was a hit on multiple charts. It reached number six on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100, number four on the Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Singles & Tracks and number one on Hot Rap Singles.<ref name=AMG-Singles /> It sold over a million units and the RIAA certified it [[RIAA certification|Platinum]] on May 23, 1995.<ref name=RIAA-Singles /> Featuring production by Combs and Chucky Thompson of The Hitmen, it samples \"[[Between the Sheets (song)|Between the Sheets]]\" by [[The Isley Brothers]]. The song was nominated at the [[Grammy Awards of 1996|1996 Grammy Awards]] for [[Best Rap Solo Performance]], but lost to [[Coolio]]'s \"[[Gangsta's Paradise (song)|Gangsta's Paradise]]\". Steve Huey named it an \"overweight-lover anthem\".<ref name=AMG />\n\n\"One More Chance\" was released as the third single on June 9, 1995. The single was a [[remix]] of the album track. It was produced by Combs and featured a sample from [[DeBarge]]'s \"Stay With Me\". It peaked at number two on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and reached number one on the Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Singles & Tracks and Hot Rap Singles.<ref name=AMG-Singles /> It sold over a million copies and the RIAA certified it Platinum on July 31, 1995.<ref name=RIAA-Singles /> Steve Huey labeled it a \"graphic sex rap\".<ref name=AMG /> ''Rolling Stone'' writer Cheo H. Coker had a similar view of the song, noting that it was \"one of the bawdiest sex raps since [[Kool G Rap]]'s classic, \"[[Talk Like Sex]]\" and continued, stating it \"proves hilarious simply because of B.I.G.'s [[Dolemite]]like vulgarity.\"<ref name=RollingStone94 />\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album reviews\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Huey\">{{cite web|last=Huey |first=Steve |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/ready-to-die-mw0000118068 |title=Ready to Die \u2013 The Notorious B.I.G. |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=October 23, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120604004502/http://www.allmusic.com/album/ready-to-die-mw0000118068 |archivedate=June 4, 2012 }}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]''\n|rev2Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Sanneh\">{{cite journal|last=Sanneh|first=Kelefa|authorlink=Kelefa Sanneh|url=http://www.blender.com/reviews/review_2710.html|title=Brooklyn drug dealer cuts rap classic, dies three years later|journal=[[Blender (magazine)|Blender]]|accessdate=July 28, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040821144238/http://www.blender.com/reviews/review_2710.html|archivedate=August 21, 2004|date=July 13, 2004|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Christgau's Consumer Guide: Albums of the '90s|Christgau's Consumer Guide]]''\n| rev3Score = A\u2212<ref name=\"Christgau\">{{cite book|chapter-url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/get_album.php?id=2599|chapter=Notorious B.I.G.: Ready to Die|accessdate=October 31, 2009|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|title=Christgau's Consumer Guide: Albums of the '90s|publisher=[[Macmillan Publishers]]|year=2000|isbn=0-312-24560-2|title-link=Christgau's Consumer Guide: Albums of the '90s}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[HipHopDX]]''\n| rev4Score = 5/5<ref>{{cite web|last=Kameka |first=Andrew |url=http://hiphopdx.com/reviews/id.761/title.the-notorious-big-ready-to-die |title=The Notorious B.I.G. \u2013 Ready To Die |work=[[HipHopDX]] |date=March 7, 2007 |accessdate=October 23, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150521180319/http://hiphopdx.com/reviews/id.761/title.the-notorious-big-ready-to-die |archivedate=May 21, 2015 }}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev5Score = 10/10<ref>{{cite web|last=Trammell |first=Matthew |url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/22952-ready-to-die/ |title=The Notorious B.I.G.: Ready to Die |work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] |date=March 9, 2017 |accessdate=March 9, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170309102528/http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/22952-ready-to-die/ |archivedate=March 9, 2017 }}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| rev6Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite journal|title=The Notorious B.I.G.: Ready to Die|journal=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|location=London|issue=99|date=December 1994}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=RollingStone94 />\n| rev8 = ''[[The Rolling Stone Album Guide]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=Hoard>{{cite book|title=The New Rolling Stone Album Guide|edition=4th|year=2004|chapter=The Notorious B.I.G.|last=Sheffield|first=Rob|authorlink=Rob Sheffield|editor1-last=Brackett|editor1-first=Nathan|editor2-last=Hoard|editor2-first=Christian|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|isbn=0-7432-0169-8|page=[https://archive.org/details/newrollingstonea00brac/page/592 592]|title-link=The Rolling Stone Album Guide}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[The Source (magazine)|The Source]]''\n| rev9Score = 4.5/5<ref name=\"Shortie\">{{cite journal|author=Shortie |url=http://pressrewind.files.wordpress.com/2007/03/biggie_source1094.jpg |title=The Notorious B.I.G.: Ready to Die |journal=[[The Source (magazine)|The Source]] |location=New York |issue=61 |date=October 1994 |accessdate=February 1, 2013 |page=79 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6E7I0chPZ |archivedate=February 1, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]''\n| rev10Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.uncut.co.uk/reviews/album/the-notorious-big-ready-to-die |title=The Notorious B.I.G. \u2013 Ready to Die |journal=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]] |location=London |issue=90 |date=November 2004 |accessdate=July 9, 2016 |page=128 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817174153/http://www.uncut.co.uk/reviews/album/the-notorious-big-ready-to-die |archivedate=August 17, 2016 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Ready to Die'' received acclaim from music critics. In his review for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', [[Cheo Hodari Coker|Cheo H. Coker]] stated \"''Ready to Die'' is the strongest solo rap debut since [[Ice Cube]]'s ''[[AmeriKKKa's Most Wanted]]''. From the breathtakingly visual moments of his birth to his [[Kurt Cobain|Cobainesque]] end in \"Suicidal Thoughts,\" B.I.G. proves a captivating listen. It's difficult to get him out of your head once you sample what he has to offer\".<ref name=RollingStone94 /> [[Robert Christgau]] from ''[[The Village Voice]]'' commented \"His sex raps are erotic, his jokes are funny, and his music makes the thug life sound scary rather than luxuriously laid back. When he considers suicide, I not only take him at his word, I actively hope he finds another way\".<ref name=Christgau /> ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote \"Though drug dealing carries tremendous heroic value with some young urban dwellers, he sacrifices the figure's romantic potential. His raps acknowledge both the excitement of drug dealing and the stress caused by the threat from other dealers, robbers, the police and parents, sometimes one's own. In presenting the downside of that life, ''Ready to Die'' offers perhaps the most balanced and honest portrait of the dealer's life of any in hip-hop\".<ref name=\"Toure\">{{cite news|author=Tour\u00e9 |authorlink=Tour\u00e9 (journalist) |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/12/18/arts/pop-music-biggie-smalls-rap-s-man-of-the-moment.html?pagewanted=3&src=pm |title=Biggie Smalls, Rap's Man of the Moment |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=December 18, 1994 |accessdate=October 23, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160309105255/http://www.nytimes.com/1994/12/18/arts/pop-music-biggie-smalls-rap-s-man-of-the-moment.html?pagewanted=3&src=pm |archivedate=March 9, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' magazine gave ''Ready to Die'' three out of five stars, and stated \"the natural rapping, clever use of sound effects and acted dialogue, and concept element (from a baby being born at the start to the fading heartbeat at the end) set this well apart from the average gangsta bragging\".<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" /> In their original review for ''Ready to Die'', ''[[The Source (magazine)|The Source]]'' gave it four-and-a-half out of five 'mics', stating \"Big weaves tales like a cinematographer, each song is like another scene in his lifestyle. Overall, this package is complete: ridiculous beats, harmonizing honeys, ill sound effects, criminal scenarios, and familiar hooks\".<ref name=Shortie />\n\n==Legacy==\n''Ready to Die'' has been highly acclaimed. In 1998, ''The Source'' included it on their  100 Best Rap Albums of All Time list,<ref name=\"accolades\" /> and in 2002, they re-rated it to the maximum five 'mics'.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Got Five on It|journal=[[The Source (magazine)|The Source]]|issue=150|date=March 2002|page=176}}</ref> ''Rolling Stone'' has also given acclaim to ''Ready to Die'' over the years. In 2003, they ranked it number 133 on their [[Rolling Stone's 500 Greatest Albums of All Time|500 Greatest Albums of All Time]] list,<ref name=\"accolades\" /> and 134 in a 2012 revised list.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web| url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/500-greatest-albums-of-all-time-156826/the-notorious-b-i-g-ready-to-die-167522/|year=2012| title=500 Greatest Albums of All Time| work= Rolling Stone | accessdate= September 18, 2019}}</ref> In 2004, they re-rated it to five stars.<ref name=\"Hoard\" /> In 2011, ''Rolling Stone'' also placed it at number eight on their 100 Best Albums of the Nineties list, and described it as \"mapping out the sound of '[[1990s in music|Nineties]] cool\".<ref name=\"1BAotN\" /> Kilian Murphy from ''[[Stylus Magazine]]'' wrote favorably of the album in a retrospective review, and concluded \"Sweet, hypocritical, sensitive, violent, depressed and jubilant; these words could all fittingly describe Big at various points on ''Ready to Die''.\"<ref name=\"Murphy\">{{cite web|last=Murphy |first=Killian |url= http://www.stylusmagazine.com/articles/on_second_thought/notorious-big-ready-to-die.htm |title=Notorious BIG \u2013 Ready to Die \u2013 On Second Thought |work=[[Stylus Magazine (magazine)|Stylus Magazine]] |date=June 22, 2004 |accessdate=October 23, 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100205082229/http://stylusmagazine.com/articles/on_second_thought/notorious-big-ready-to-die.htm |archivedate= February 5, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nSteve Huey from [[AllMusic]] gave it five stars, stating \"The album that reinvented East Coast rap for the gangsta age, ''Ready to Die'' made the Notorious B.I.G. a star. Today it's recognized as one of the greatest hardcore rap albums ever recorded, and that's mostly due to Biggie's skill as a storyteller\".<ref name=Huey /> In 2006, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine included it on their 100 Greatest Albums of All Time list, and stated \"On ''Ready to Die'', [[Notorious B.I.G.|Wallace]] took his street corner experiences and filtered them through his considerable charm. The result was a record that mixed long stretches of menace with romance and lots of humor. No rapper ever made multi-syllabic rhymes sound as smooth\".<ref name=TIME>{{cite web| last1= Tyrangiel |first1=Josh |title=All-TIME 100 Albums |url=http://entertainment.time.com/2006/11/02/the-all-time-100-albums/slide/ready-to-die/ |website=Time |accessdate=July 11, 2017 |date=January 22, 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170130024040/http://entertainment.time.com/2006/11/02/the-all-time-100-albums/slide/ready-to-die/ |archivedate=January 30, 2017 }}</ref> The album was also included in the book ''[[1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die]]''.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Robert Dimery|author2=Michael Lydon|title=1001 Albums You Must Hear Before You Die: Revised and Updated Edition|accessdate= |date=March 23, 2010|publisher=Universe|isbn=978-0-7893-2074-2}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n*<small>The information regarding accolades is adapted from Acclaimedmusic.net,</small><ref name=\"accolades\">[http://www.acclaimedmusic.net/Current/A921.htm Acclaimedmusic.net] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100616110314/http://acclaimedmusic.net/Current/A921.htm |date=June 16, 2010 }}</ref><small>except where noted.</small>\n*<small>(*) signifies unordered lists</small>\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Publication\n! Country\n! Accolade\n! Year\n! Rank\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[About.com]]\n|rowspan=4|[[United States]]\n|''100 Greatest Hip Hop Albums''<ref>{{cite web|title=100 Best Hip-Hop Albums of All Time |url= http://rap.about.com/od/toppicks/ss/Top100RapAlbums_10.htm |website=ThoughtCo |accessdate=July 11, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150405151731/http://rap.about.com/od/toppicks/ss/Top100RapAlbums_10.htm |arc