{"title_page": "Wen Tingyun", "text_new": "{{Chinese\n|pic=Wen Tingyun.jpg\n|t=\u6eab\u5ead\u7b60\n|s=\u6e29\u5ead\u7b60\n|p=W\u0113n T\u012bngy\u016bn\n|w=W\u00ean T'ing-y\u00fcn\n|j=Wan<sup>1</sup> Ting<sup>4</sup>-wan<sup>4</sup>\n|mc=\u0241w\u0259n Dieng-jwen\n}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Wen (surname)|Wen]]}}\n'''Wen Tingyun''' ({{zh|t=\u6eab\u5ead\u7b60|s=\u6e29\u5ead\u7b60}}; 812&ndash;870) born '''Wen Qi''' ({{zh|t=\u6eab\u6b67|s=\u6e29\u6b67|p=W\u0113n Q\u00ed}}), [[courtesy name]] '''Feiqing''' ({{zh|t=\u98db\u537f|s=\u98de\u537f|p=F\u0113iq\u012bng}}) was a Chinese poet. He was an important [[China|Chinese]] [[lyricist]] of the late [[Tang Dynasty]].\n\nHe was born in [[Qi County, Shanxi|Qi]], [[Shanxi province]], [[China]].  Over his literary career, Wen became regarded as the first truly distinctive writer of ''[[Ci (poetry)|ci]]'', the song-verse style of poetry that dominated [[Chinese poetry]] during much of the late Tang dynasty and the [[Song dynasty]].<ref>Stephen Owen, ''An Anthology of Chinese Literature: Beginnings to 1911'' (New York, London: W.W. Norton, 1996): 565.</ref>  Most of his poems are \"[[boudoir]]\"-style verses that described the opulent furnishings and gardens of solitary women and their hidden desires.<ref name=\"owen565\">Owen (1996): 565.</ref> This style of poetry was commonly used for romantic communications between men and women in the entertainment districts of the Chinese capital [[Chang'an]] during the Tang dynasty.<ref name=\"owen565\" />\n\nHis son [[Wen Xian]](\u6e29\u61b2) was also a poet.<ref>\u300a\u5168\u5510\u8a69\u300b\u5377667</ref>\n\n==References==\n;Citations\n{{Reflist}}\n\n;Works cited\n*{{citation\n | title = An Anthology of Chinese Literature: Beginnings to 1911\n | last = Owen | first = Stephen\n | place = New York, London | publisher = W.W. Norton | year = 1996\n | postscript = .\n | isbn = 0393971066\n }}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*  Mou, Huaichuan \u725f\u6000\u5ddd. ''Rediscovering Wen Tingyun'' {{ISBN|0791459365}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/639682/Wen-Tingyun Biography on Britannica]\n* [http://bosp.kcc.hawaii.edu/Horizons/horizons_1999/chinese_poets2.html Poetry of the era]\n* {{Librivox author |id=3158}}\n*Books of the ''[[Quan Tangshi]]'' that include collected poems of Wen Tingyun at the [[Chinese Text Project]]:\n**[http://ctext.org/quantangshi/575 Book 575], [http://ctext.org/quantangshi/576 Book 576], [http://ctext.org/quantangshi/577 Book 577], [http://ctext.org/quantangshi/578 Book 578], [http://ctext.org/quantangshi/579 Book 579],\n**[http://ctext.org/quantangshi/580 Book 580], [http://ctext.org/quantangshi/581 Book 581], [http://ctext.org/quantangshi/582 Book 582], [http://ctext.org/quantangshi/583 Book 583]\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wen, Tingyun}}\n[[Category:812 births]]\n[[Category:870 deaths]]\n[[Category:9th-century Chinese poets]]\n[[Category:Chinese lyricists]]\n[[Category:People from Jinzhong]]\n[[Category:Poets from Shanxi]]\n[[Category:Tang dynasty poets]]\n\n\n{{China-poet-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Chinese\n|pic=Wen Tingyun.jpg\n|t=\u6eab\u5ead\u7b60\n|s=\u6e29\u5ead\u7b60\n|p=W\u0113n T\u012bngy\u016bn\n|w=W\u00ean T'ing-y\u00fcn\n|j=Wan<sup>1</sup> Ting<sup>4</sup>-wan<sup>4</sup>\n|mc=\u0241w\u0259n Dieng-jwen\n}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Wen (surname)|Wen]]}}\n'''Wen Tingyun''' ({{zh|t=\u6eab\u5ead\u7b60|s=\u6e29\u5ead\u7b60}}; 812&ndash;870) born '''Wen Qi''' ({{zh|t=\u6eab\u6b67|s=\u6e29\u6b67|p=W\u0113n Q\u00ed}}), [[courtesy name]] '''Feiqing''' ({{zh|t=\u98db\u537f|s=\u98de\u537f|p=F\u0113iq\u012bng}}) was a Chinese poet. He was an important [[China|Chinese]] [[lyricist]] of the late [[Tang Dynasty]]. \n\nHe was born in [[Qi County, Shanxi|Qi]], [[Shanxi province]], [[China]].  Over his literary career, Wen became regarded as the first truly distinctive writer of ''[[Ci (poetry)|ci]]'', the song-verse style of poetry that dominated [[Chinese poetry]] during much of the late Tang dynasty and the [[Song dynasty]].<ref>Stephen Owen, ''An Anthology of Chinese Literature: Beginnings to 1911'' (New York, London: W.W. Norton, 1996): 565.</ref>  Most of his poems are \"[[boudoir]]\"-style verses that described the opulent furnishings and gardens of solitary women and their hidden desires.<ref name=\"owen565\">Owen (1996): 565.</ref> This style of poetry was commonly used for romantic communications between men and women in the entertainment districts of the Chinese capital [[Chang'an]] during the Tang dynasty.<ref name=\"owen565\" />\n\nHis son [[Wen Xian]](\u6e29\u61b2) was also a poet.<ref>\u300a\u5168\u5510\u8a69\u300b\u5377667</ref>\n\n==References==\n;Citations\n{{Reflist}}\n\n;Works cited\n*{{citation\n | title = An Anthology of Chinese Literature: Beginnings to 1911\n | last = Owen | first = Stephen\n | place = New York, London | publisher = W.W. Norton | year = 1996\n | postscript = .\n | isbn = 0393971066\n }}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*  Mou, Huaichuan \u725f\u6000\u5ddd. ''Rediscovering Wen Tingyun'' {{ISBN|0791459365}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/639682/Wen-Tingyun Biography on Britannica]\n* [http://bosp.kcc.hawaii.edu/Horizons/horizons_1999/chinese_poets2.html Poetry of the era]\n* {{Librivox author |id=3158}}\n*Books of the ''[[Quan Tangshi]]'' that include collected poems of Wen Tingyun at the [[Chinese Text Project]]:\n**[http://ctext.org/quantangshi/575 Book 575], [http://ctext.org/quantangshi/576 Book 576], [http://ctext.org/quantangshi/577 Book 577], [http://ctext.org/quantangshi/578 Book 578], [http://ctext.org/quantangshi/579 Book 579],\n**[http://ctext.org/quantangshi/580 Book 580], [http://ctext.org/quantangshi/581 Book 581], [http://ctext.org/quantangshi/582 Book 582], [http://ctext.org/quantangshi/583 Book 583]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wen, Tingyun}}\n\n[[Category:812 births]]\n[[Category:870 deaths]]\n[[Category:9th-century Chinese poets]]\n[[Category:Chinese lyricists]]\n[[Category:People from Jinzhong]]\n[[Category:Poets from Shanxi]]\n[[Category:Tang dynasty poets]]\n\n\n{{China-poet-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wen_Tingyun"}
{"title_page": "The Golden Child (novel)", "text_new": "{{About|the Penelope Fitzgerald novel|the 1986 Eddie Murphy movie|The Golden Child}}\n{{See also|Golden Child (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|1977 novel by Penelope Fitzgerald}}\n\n{{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books -->\n| name          = The Golden Child\n| image         = Golden Child, Penelope Fitzgerald, cover.jpg\n| cover_artist  = \n| caption       = Cover to first edition\n| author        = [[Penelope Fitzgerald]]\n| country       = [[United Kingdom]]\n| language      = [[English language|English]]\n| publisher     = [[Duckworth Overlook|Duckworth]]<ref name=\"BLcat\">{{Cite web |url=http://primocat.bl.uk/F?func=direct&local_base=ITEMV&doc_number=008091459&con_lng=eng |title=British Library Item details |website=primocat.bl.uk |access-date=26 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n| published     = 1977<ref name=\"BLcat\"/>\n\n| media_type    = Print\n| pages         = 159<ref name=\"BLcat\"/>\n| isbn          = \n| congress      = \n| oclc          = \n}}\n'''''The Golden Child''''' is a 1977 [[Mystery fiction|mystery novel]]<ref name=\"SaumarezSmith\">{{Cite book |title=Introduction |last=Saumarez Smith |first=Charles |work=The Golden Child |publisher=Fourth Estate |year=2014 |isbn=978-0-00-654625-2 |location=London |page=x |author-link=Charles Saumarez Smith}}</ref> by the British author [[Penelope Fitzgerald]], her first published work of fiction. Written while her husband was terminally ill, and partly for his benefit, the novel offers a satirical version of the [[Exhibitions of artifacts from the tomb of Tutankhamun#The Treasures of Tutankhamun (1972\u20131981)|''1972 Treasures of Tutankhamun exhibition'']] at the [[British Museum]], and pokes fun at museum politics, academic scholars, and Cold War spying.\n\n== Plot ==\nIn January 1973,{{sfn|Lee|2013|p=240}} London, the Museum is exhibiting for the first time anywhere the golden [[Garamantes|Garamantian]] treasures, on loan from the Garamantian government, that had been discovered years earlier by the eminent archaeologist Sir William Simpkin. Sir William, wealthy and now elderly, is retained by the Museum as a figurehead, largely because the Museum\u2019s director, Sir John Allison, expects to receive a large bequest on the old man's death. Huge crowds queue for hours for a brief glimpse under poor lighting of the two most famous exhibits: the Golden Child and the Ball of Golden Twine. Rumours circulate that the Child is cursed.\n\nSir William shows little interest in the exhibition, but he does ask to take a closer look at one of the many [[clay tablet]]s that accompany the treasures. Late at night, while returning the tablet to its case at Sir William\u2019s request, a Junior Exhibition Officer, Waring Smith, is attacked and partly strangled, apparently with the Golden Twine.\n\nWhen the German Garamantologist Professor Untermensch tells the Director that all the artefacts in the exhibition are fakes, Sir John decides that a second opinion is needed.&nbsp; This has to be obtained covertly because of the political sensitivities of the government loan, and he dispatches Smith to Moscow, along with one of the lesser treasures, to get the opinion of the word-famous Russian Garamantologist Professor Semyonov. The Director expects that no one will be suspicious of Smith because of his lowly position. Untermensch, however, thinks that the Soviets will assume he is a spy, and he shadows him. The Soviets do indeed make that assumption and - to show that they know the game the British are playing - they allow Smith and Untermensch into the [[Moscow Kremlin|Kremlin]] to view the real Garamantian treasure. Smith discovers that there is no such person as Semyonov.\n\nSmith returns, demoralised, and is temporarily detained on his arrival by a man from the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] who wants to know what his business was in Russia. Trying to explain himself, he invokes Sir William whom he expects will clarify his trip - only to learn that Sir William has been found dead, trapped between two sliding steel shelf units in the Museum library. A warder, Jones, is also later found dead: he has fallen from a fifth story window.\n\nLen Coker, a Museum technician, reveals that the tablet Smith took back to its case was a fake that he had made himself on Sir William\u2019s instructions. Untermensch decodes the Garamantian characters to reveal Sir William\u2019s message: that he revokes his bequest to Sir John Allison. Accused of murder, Sir John pulls a gun and flees. Cornered, he shoots himself and crashes down on the exhibits, revealing them for the fakes they truly are. The staff patch up the exhibits so that they look convincing in the dim light, just in time for the evening opening.\n\n== Principal characters ==\n\n* Sir William Simpkin: elderly archaeologist, discoverer of the Golden Child\n* Sir John Allison: Museum Director\n* Marcus Hawthorne-Mannering: Keeper of Funerary Art\n* Waring Smith: Junior Exhibition Officer\n* Professor Heinrich Untermensch: German Garamantologist\n* Dr Tite-Live Rochegrosse-Bergson (Schwarz): French cultural anthropologist\n* Professor Cyril Ivanovitch Semyonov: Supposed Russian Garamantologist\n* Jones Jones: Warder, unofficial retainer to Sir William\n* Len Coker: Technician, Conservation and Technical Services Department.\n* Dousha Vartarian: Secretary to Sir William Simpkin\n* Miss Rank: Secretary to Sir John Allison.\n\n== Background ==\n\nFitzgerald wrote the novel to amuse her husband, who was terminally ill with [[Colorectal cancer|bowel cancer]].{{sfn | Lee | 2013 | p=235}} She had also wanted to deal with the annoyance she had felt when visiting [[Exhibitions of artifacts from the tomb of Tutankhamun#The Treasures of Tutankhamun (1972\u20131981)|''The Treasures of Tutankhamun exhibition'']] at the [[British Museum]] in 1972 (having speculated that everything in it was a forgery), and also to write about someone who had been unpleasant to her when she was visiting museums to research her book on [[Edward Burne-Jones|Burne-Jones]].{{sfn | Lee | 2013 | p=235}}\n\nFitzgerald\u2019s original manuscript for the novel - to be called ''The Golden Opinion'' - was much longer than the published version.{{sfn | Lee | 2013 | p=240}} It included chapters on the continuing cover-up of the fraud, as well as scenes in which the [[Cabinet Secretary (United Kingdom)|Cabinet Secretary]] discusses the possibility of public disorder sparked by the fake exhibition. The publisher told her that they needed to be cut, along with the entirety of a sub-plot and several additional characters.{{sfn | Lee | 2013 | pp=240, 244-247}}\n \nFitzgerald's publisher suggested that she should write more novels featuring Professor Untermensch as a recurring detective.{{sfn | Lee | 2013 | p=250}} She did indeed start work on two Untermensch thrillers{{sfn | Lee | 2013 | p=250}} but in the end thought it best not to be typecast.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Fitzgerald|first=Penelope|date=September 24, 1994|title=Second Thoughts: Art critic without a clue: Penelope Fitzgerald on the brush with crime that made her decide to go straight|page=Books 27|work=The Independent}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n\n[[H. R. F. Keating|HRF Keating]], reviewing the book as a crime novel for ''[[The Times]]'' referred to the novel\u2019s good joking, if occasionally in-joking; muted social criticism; and good writing, if somewhat consciously so.<ref name=\"Keating\">{{Cite news |title=Crime:  |last=Keating |first=HRF |author-link=H. R. F. Keating |date=6 October 1977 |work=[[The Times]]  |at=Arts and Sports, p. 20}}</ref>\n\nWriting in the ''[[Library Journal]]'', Henri C. Veit called the novel \"A muddle of violence and intrigue that I wouldn't have missed for the world.\"<ref>{{cite journal|last=Veit|first=Henri C.|title=The Golden Child|work=Library Journal|date=1 April 1979|volume=104|issue=7|page=850}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2014 introduction to the Fourth Estate paperback re-issue, [[Charles Saumarez Smith]] called the book \"taut, finely plotted [and] richly comic, with some of the elements of exaggerated satire characteristic of a campus novel\".<ref name=\"SaumarezSmith\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{Cite book | ref=harv | title=Penelope Fitzgerald: A Life |last= Lee |first=Hermione |publisher=[[Chatto & Windus]] |year=2013 |location=London |author-link=Hermione Lee |isbn=9780701184957}}\n* {{cite book|last=Wolfe|first=Peter|title=Understanding Penelope Fitzgerald|publisher=University of South Carolina Press|year=2004|ref=harv|chapter=The Great Museum Sideshow}}\n{{Penelope Fitzgerald}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Golden Boy, The}}\n[[Category:1977 British novels]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in 1973]]\n[[Category:Novels by Penelope Fitzgerald]]\n[[Category:Novels about museums]]\n[[Category:Cold War spy novels]]\n[[Category:British crime novels]]\n[[Category:Novels set in London]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Moscow]]\n[[Category:Gerald Duckworth and Company books]]\n[[Category:1977 debut novels]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the Penelope Fitzgerald novel|the 1986 Eddie Murphy movie|The Golden Child}}\n{{See also|Golden Child (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|1977 novel by Penelope Fitzgerald}}\n\n{{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books -->\n| name          = The Golden Child\n| image         = Golden Child, Penelope Fitzgerald, cover.jpg\n| cover_artist  = \n| caption       = Cover to first edition\n| author        = [[Penelope Fitzgerald]]\n| country       = [[United Kingdom]]\n| language      = [[English language|English]]\n| publisher     = [[Duckworth Overlook|Duckworth]]<ref name=\"BLcat\">{{Cite web |url=http://primocat.bl.uk/F?func=direct&local_base=ITEMV&doc_number=008091459&con_lng=eng |title=British Library Item details |website=primocat.bl.uk |access-date=26 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n| published     = 1977<ref name=\"BLcat\"/>\n\n| media_type    = Print\n| pages         = 159<ref name=\"BLcat\"/>\n| isbn          = \n| congress      = \n| oclc          = \n}}\n'''''The Golden Child''''' is a 1977 [[Mystery fiction|mystery novel]]<ref name=\"SaumarezSmith\">{{Cite book |title=Introduction |last=Saumarez Smith |first=Charles |work=The Golden Child |publisher=Fourth Estate |year=2014 |isbn=978-0-00-654625-2 |location=London |page=x |author-link=Charles Saumarez Smith}}</ref> by the British author [[Penelope Fitzgerald]], her first published work of fiction. Written while her husband was terminally ill, and partly for his benefit, the novel offers a satirical version of the [[Exhibitions of artifacts from the tomb of Tutankhamun#The Treasures of Tutankhamun (1972\u20131981)|''1972 Treasures of Tutankhamun exhibition'']] at the [[British Museum]], and pokes fun at museum politics, academic scholars, and Cold War spying.\n\n== Plot ==\nIn January 1973,{{sfn|Lee|2013|p=240}} London, the Museum is exhibiting for the first time anywhere the golden [[Garamantes|Garamantian]] treasures, on loan from the Garamantian government, that had been discovered years earlier by the eminent archaeologist Sir William Simpkin. Sir William, wealthy and now elderly, is retained by the Museum as a figurehead, largely because the Museum\u2019s director, Sir John Allison, expects to receive a large bequest on the old man's death. Huge crowds queue for hours for a brief glimpse under poor lighting of the two most famous exhibits: the Golden Child and the Ball of Golden Twine. Rumours circulate that the Child is cursed.\n\nSir William shows little interest in the exhibition, but he does ask to take a closer look at one of the many [[clay tablet]]s that accompany the treasures. Late at night, while returning the tablet to its case at Sir William\u2019s request, a Junior Exhibition Officer, Waring Smith, is attacked and partly strangled, apparently with the Golden Twine.\n\nWhen the German Garamantologist Professor Untermensch tells the Director that all the artefacts in the exhibition are fakes, Sir John decides that a second opinion is needed.&nbsp; This has to be obtained covertly because of the political sensitivities of the government loan, and he dispatches Smith to Moscow, along with one of the lesser treasures, to get the opinion of the word-famous Russian Garamantologist Professor Semyonov. The Director expects that no one will be suspicious of Smith because of his lowly position. Untermensch, however, thinks that the Soviets will assume he is a spy, and he shadows him. The Soviets do indeed make that assumption and - to show that they know the game the British are playing - they allow Smith and Untermensch into the [[Moscow Kremlin|Kremlin]] to view the real Garamantian treasure. Smith discovers that there is no such person as Semyonov.\n\nSmith returns, demoralised, and is temporarily detained on his arrival by a man from the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Defence]] who wants to know what his business was in Russia. Trying to explain himself, he invokes Sir William whom he expects will clarify his trip - only to learn that Sir William has been found dead, trapped between two sliding steel shelf units in the Museum library. A warder, Jones, is also later found dead: he has fallen from a fifth story window.\n\nLen Coker, a Museum technician, reveals that the tablet Smith took back to its case was a fake that he had made himself on Sir William\u2019s instructions. Untermensch decodes the Garamantian characters to reveal Sir William\u2019s message: that he revokes his bequest to Sir John Allison. Accused of murder, Sir John pulls a gun and flees. Cornered, he shoots himself and crashes down on the exhibits, revealing them for the fakes they truly are. The staff patch up the exhibits so that they look convincing in the dim light, just in time for the evening opening.\n\n== Principal characters ==\n\n* Sir William Simpkin: elderly archaeologist, discoverer of the Golden Child\n* Sir John Allison: Museum Director\n* Marcus Hawthorne-Mannering: Keeper of Funerary Art\n* Waring Smith: Junior Exhibition Officer\n* Professor Heinrich Untermensch: German Garamantologist\n* Dr Tite-Live Rochegrosse-Bergson (Schwarz): French cultural anthropologist\n* Professor Cyril Ivanovitch Semyonov: Supposed Russian Garamantologist\n* Jones Jones: Warder, unofficial retainer to Sir William\n* Len Coker: Technician, Conservation and Technical Services Department.\n* Dousha Vartarian: Secretary to Sir William Simpkin\n* Miss Rank: Secretary to Sir John Allison.\n\n== Background ==\n\nFitzgerald wrote the novel to amuse her husband, who was terminally ill with [[Colorectal cancer|bowel cancer]].{{sfn | Lee | 2013 | p=235}} She had also wanted to deal with the annoyance she had felt when visiting [[Exhibitions of artifacts from the tomb of Tutankhamun#The Treasures of Tutankhamun (1972\u20131981)|''The Treasures of Tutankhamun exhibition'']] at the [[British Museum]] in 1972 (having speculated that everything in it was a forgery), and also to write about someone who had been unpleasant to her when she was visiting museums to research her book on [[Edward Burne-Jones|Burne-Jones]].{{sfn | Lee | 2013 | p=235}}\n\nFitzgerald\u2019s original manuscript for the novel - to be called ''The Golden Opinion'' - was much longer than the published version.{{sfn | Lee | 2013 | p=240}} It included chapters on the continuing cover-up of the fraud, as well as scenes in which the [[Cabinet Secretary (United Kingdom)|Cabinet Secretary]] discusses the possibility of public disorder sparked by the fake exhibition. The publisher told her that they needed to be cut, along with the entirety of an sub-plot and several additional characters.{{sfn | Lee | 2013 | pp=240, 244-247}}\n \nFitzgerald's publisher suggested that she should write more novels featuring Professor Untermensch as a recurring detective.{{sfn | Lee | 2013 | p=250}} She did indeed start work on two Untermensch thrillers{{sfn | Lee | 2013 | p=250}} but in the end thought it best not to be typecast.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Fitzgerald|first=Penelope|date=September 24, 1994|title=Second Thoughts: Art critic without a clue: Penelope Fitzgerald on the brush with crime that made her decide to go straight|page=Books 27|work=The Independent}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n\n[[H. R. F. Keating|HRF Keating]], reviewing the book as a crime novel for ''[[The Times]]'' referred to the novel\u2019s good joking, if occasionally in-joking; muted social criticism; and good writing, if somewhat consciously so.<ref name=\"Keating\">{{Cite news |title=Crime:  |last=Keating |first=HRF |author-link=H. R. F. Keating |date=6 October 1977 |work=[[The Times]]  |at=Arts and Sports, p. 20}}</ref>\n\nWriting in the ''[[Library Journal]]'', Henri C. Veit called the novel \"A muddle of violence and intrigue that I wouldn't have missed for the world.\"<ref>{{cite journal|last=Veit|first=Henri C.|title=The Golden Child|work=Library Journal|date=1 April 1979|volume=104|issue=7|page=850}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2014 introduction to the Fourth Estate paperback re-issue, [[Charles Saumarez Smith]] called the book \"taut, finely plotted [and] richly comic, with some of the elements of exaggerated satire characteristic of a campus novel\".<ref name=\"SaumarezSmith\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{Cite book | ref=harv | title=Penelope Fitzgerald: A Life |last= Lee |first=Hermione |publisher=[[Chatto & Windus]] |year=2013 |location=London |author-link=Hermione Lee |isbn=9780701184957}}\n* {{cite book|last=Wolfe|first=Peter|title=Understanding Penelope Fitzgerald|publisher=University of South Carolina Press|year=2004|ref=harv|chapter=The Great Museum Sideshow}}\n{{Penelope Fitzgerald}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Golden Boy, The}}\n[[Category:1977 British novels]]\n[[Category:Fiction set in 1973]]\n[[Category:Novels by Penelope Fitzgerald]]